{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491055"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:30:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:30:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"819"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/819"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.03,0.49,0.21,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/819"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91213"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5488"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44761"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents with a one month history of jaundice, tiredness and increasing pain in the upper abdomen, which goes through to her back. She has lost about 10kg in weight. Over the last four days she has noticed that her urine has been dark and frothy and her faeces are pale. Despite the weight loss, she is obese and no abnormalities are found on examination of the abdomen. She has been smoking for the last 40 years and has been drinking alcohol on special occasions, about once a month. She has no history of previous illnesses. A number of investigations are arranged, including ultrasonography of the upper abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would this be most likely to show?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A dilated, thickened gallbladder, containing stones","Normal liver parenchyma with a normal intrahepatic biliary system","A dilated biliary system","A dilated pancreatic duct and normal common bile duct","A dilated common bile duct containing stones and normal intrahepatic bile ducts"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIf the clinician thought that the patient\u0027s problem was related to gallstones, an ultrasound would be an appropriate investigation. However, the story is more suggestive of carcinoma of the pancreas and with that diagnosis in mind, a CT scan might have been more useful. In obese patients, abdominal ultrasound can be of limited value, particularly when looking at retroperitoneal structures. In the present circumstances, the only supportive evidence of an obstructing pancreatic cancer might be the \u003Cstrong\u003Epresence of a dilated biliary tree\u003C/strong\u003E - the pancreas itself might not be visible on the ultrasound. A malignancy in the head of the pancreas is very likely to progress by local extension to compress surrounding structures - and one of these will be the lower end of the common bile duct. If this becomes compressed and obstructed, there will be proximal duct dilatation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver parenchyma and intrahepatic biliary duct\u003C/strong\u003E may be normal but is not the optimal choice as it does not suggest the findings of pancreatic cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholelithiasis (gallstones in the gallbladder)\u003C/strong\u003E with symptoms would present with constant dull pain in the RUQ region that lasts less than 6 hours and apparent after meals (postprandial pain). \u003Cstrong\u003ECholedocholithiasis (gallstones in the common bile duct)\u003C/strong\u003E is generally seen in patients that have migrated gallstones from the gallbladder into the common bile duct. These patients would have RUQ pain lasting more than 6 hours which is also postprandial. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntrahepatic cholestasis (dilated intrahepatic biliary system)\u003C/strong\u003E is mainly found in patients with PBC, which is found in women with associated autoimmune conditions such as IBD, celiac disease or Hashimoto thyroiditis or PSC, which is associated with ulcerative colitis. Dilated pancreatic duct with normal common bile duct (single duct dilation) is associated with chronic pancreatitis which the patient does not have due to absent medical history. Pancreatic cancer is commonly seen in double duct dilatation (main pancreatic duct dilation with concomitant biliary duct dilatation).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic cancer patients generally have double duct dilation (both dilation of the main pancreatic duct and biliary duct)."],"references":["Saini S. Imaging of the hepatobiliary tract. N Engl J Med. 1997 Jun 26;336(26):1889-94. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9197218/","DiMagno EP, Malagelada JR, Taylor WF, Go VL. A prospective comparison of current diagnostic tests for pancreatic cancer. N Engl J Med. 1977 Oct 6;297(14):737-42. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/895803/","Edge MD, Hoteit M, Patel AP, Wang X, Baumgarten DA, Cai Q. Clinical significance of main pancreatic duct dilation on computed tomography: single and double duct dilation. World J Gastroenterol. 2007 Mar 21;13(11):1701-5. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4146949/","Lee TY. Optimal Evaluation of Suspected Choledocholithiasis: Does This Patient Really Have Choledocholithiasis?. Clinical endoscopy .2017; 50(5): p.415-416. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5642062/","Tazuma S, Unno M, Igarashi Y, et al. Evidence-based clinical practice guidelines for cholelithiasis 2016. J Gastroenterol .2016; 52(3): p.276-300. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27942871/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91213"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"819"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91213"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T19:25:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T19:25:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"819"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nu